    bio_en: "Over a thousand years ago, while Europe was mired in the Dark Ages and literary culture was largely confined to religious texts, a lady-in-waiting at the Japanese imperial court was quietly writing what many scholars consider the world's first novel. Murasaki Shikibu's 'The Tale of Genji' is a masterpiece of psychological depth, narrative complexity, and poetic beauty that still astounds readers today.\n\nWritten in the early 11th century, The Tale of Genji follows the romantic adventures and political intrigues of Prince Genji, the dazzlingly handsome son of a Japanese emperor. But what makes the work revolutionary is not its plot — it's Murasaki's extraordinary ability to capture the inner emotional lives of her characters with a subtlety and sophistication that wouldn't be matched in Western literature for centuries.\n\nLittle is known about Murasaki herself — even her real name is lost to history (Murasaki Shikibu is a nickname). She was born into the Fujiwara clan, was widowed young, and served at the court of Empress Shoshi. Her diary reveals a woman of sharp intelligence who sometimes felt isolated by her own learning, noting that other court ladies called her pretentious for knowing Chinese characters — a skill considered unfeminine at the time.",
    bio_zh: "一千多年前，当欧洲还深陷黑暗时代、文学文化主要局限于宗教典籍时，日本皇宫中一位女官正在静静地书写着被许多学者认为是世界上第一部小说的作品。紫式部的《源氏物语》以其心理深度、叙事复杂性和诗意之美，至今仍令读者叹为观止。\n\n《源氏物语》写于11世纪初，讲述了光源氏——一位日本天皇风度翩翩的皇子——的浪漫冒险与政治阴谋。但使这部作品具有革命性意义的不是它的情节，而是紫式部捕捉人物内心情感世界的非凡能力，其细腻与深邃在此后数百年间的西方文学中都无人能及。\n\n关于紫式部本人的记载寥寥无几——甚至她的真名都已失传（紫式部只是一个别称）。她出身藤原氏，年轻时丧夫，后入宫侍奉彰子皇后。她的日记展现了一位才智敏锐却时常因自己的学识而感到孤立的女性——她提到其他宫女嘲笑她矫揉造作，因为她懂得汉字，而这在当时被认为不够女性化。",
