    title_zh: "皇宫中最犀利的才女",
    bio_en: "If Murasaki Shikibu invented the novel, her contemporary and rival Sei Shonagon invented the personal essay. Her 'Pillow Book' is a dazzling, wildly original collection of observations, lists, gossip, opinions, and anecdotes from life at the Heian imperial court. It's funny, catty, brutally honest, and reads as fresh today as when it was written over a millennium ago.\n\nSei Shonagon served as a lady-in-waiting to Empress Teishi, the rival of Murasaki's patron Empress Shoshi. She was famous for her razor-sharp wit and her ability to compose poetry instantly in social situations — a crucial skill in Heian court culture, where a slow or clumsy poem could destroy your reputation. Her confidence bordered on arrogance, and she clearly relished intellectual combat.\n\nThe Pillow Book is full of delightful lists like 'Hateful Things,' 'Elegant Things,' 'Things That Make Your Heart Beat Faster,' and 'Awkward Things.' Her observations range from the profound to the petty, capturing the texture of daily life with an immediacy that makes the Heian court feel strangely relatable across the centuries. Murasaki Shikibu reportedly couldn't stand her, writing in her diary that Sei Shonagon was insufferably smug — which honestly just makes both writers more interesting.",
    bio_zh: "如果说紫式部发明了小说，那么她的同时代人兼对手清少纳言则发明了随笔。她的《枕草子》是一部令人眼花缭乱、极具独创性的作品集，汇集了对平安朝宫廷生活的观察、清单、闲话、见解和轶事。它诙谐、毒舌、坦率得近乎残酷，读起来和千年前写就时一样鲜活生动。\n\n清少纳言曾侍奉定子皇后——她是紫式部的主人彰子皇后的对手。清少纳言以其刀锋般锐利的机智和即兴作诗的能力闻名——在平安宫廷文化中，这是一项至关重要的技能，一首迟钝或笨拙的诗可能毁掉你的名声。她的自信近乎傲慢，显然乐于智识上的交锋。\n\n《枕草子》中充满了令人愉悦的清单，如「可憎之事」「优雅之事」「令人心跳加速之事」和「尴尬之事」。她的观察从深刻到琐碎无所不包，以一种跨越千年仍令人感同身受的即视感捕捉了日常生活的质感。据说紫式部受不了她，在日记中写道清少纳言自鸣得意到令人难以忍受——但老实说这反而让两位作家都更加有趣了。",
    whyFamous_en: "Author of The Pillow Book, one of the world's earliest and most influential works of personal essay writing, offering a vivid window into Heian court life.",
    whyFamous_zh: "《枕草子》的作者，世界上最早且最具影响力的随笔作品之一，为后人打开了一扇了解平安朝宫廷生活的生动窗口。",
    funFact_en: "The title 'Pillow Book' may refer to notebooks kept inside wooden pillow-drawers, which were used as private diaries — essentially the Heian equivalent of a locked diary under the mattress.",
    funFact_zh: "《枕草子》的书名可能源于放在木枕抽屉里的笔记本，用作私人日记——本质上就是平安时代版的「藏在床垫下的上锁日记」。",
